"When I was first exposed to this career it was just so mind blowing that you could go out in a helicopter and provide the same care you do at the bedside at 2,000 feet, flying 160 miles per hour.  From then on I was hooked.  I knew this was what I wanted to do and where my career was going to go. When you come in at the beginning of a shift, you never know what vehicle you are going to take, it could be a helicopter, jet or ambulance.  You never know whether you are going to stay in the state of Michigan or go to Haiti. You never know whether you will be home that night or staying in a hotel somewhere. For me that's the draw. I love the unpredictability, I hate doing the same thing every day. You need to be able to adapt and move quickly and go with the flow. That's what keeps me coming back after all these years. I never do the same thing two days in a row." #WolverinesOfAnnArbor

"College is kind of like the first point in your life where you don't have parental supervision and you can do a lot with minimal consequences. It opens the door to a lot of experimentation, which can go bad, and it teaches you to juggle nasty things at the same time; things going wrong between academics and social life, and what not. It's a time when you kind of just have to figure it out on your own." 

What would you say through your college experience was the moment that stood out to you the most?
"It's been a long time. I came from abroad, Egypt, and so that was quite a distance away from my family. And so, right off the get go, I came to orientation without any of my friends or family near me and I just had to figure out everything on my own. It hit me right then and there that, you know, I'm alone for the next four years. Not entirely alone, but I have to function on my own for the next four years. Four years down the road, I'm almost there." 

Why did you choose the University of Michigan?
"I wanted to go abroad to study astrophysics, which is actually what I'm doing right now. I'm doing research on black holes. I couldn't find that back home, so I had to look abroad." #WolverinesOfAnnArbor

70 years ago tomorrow, Ann Arbor, like many cities across the nation, gathered together in celebration. On August 14, 1945, a great joy swept through the country as the Japanese had surrendered, signaling the end of the World War II.  People spontaneously ran into the streets when they heard the news, flocking to Main Street, which was soon jammed with cars and people.  The celebration lasted far into the night and classes were cancelled the next day. #ThrowbackThursday from Bentley Historical Library

Photo highlights from the 2014 MCubed Symposium on Thursday, October 9, 2014 in Rackham Auditorium and The Michigan League. The MCubed Symposium provides the opportunity for teams of faculty "cubes" to showcase their innovative research at this campus-wide event.

The MCubed Initiative distributes real-time seed funding to multi-unit teams of faculty engaged in innovative research and scholarship, enabling them to keep pace with the rapid information flow of today's dynamic research environment.  It allows faculty teams to address major social problems too complex for a single disciplinary approach‚Äîand to pursue experimental approaches that might be too unconventional to attract immediate support from more traditional funding mechanisms.  

For more information about the MCubed Initiative, please visit: http://mcubed.umich.edu/

Students & Staff:

Ann Arbor Campus classes have been canceled for tomorrow Tuesday, January 28th due to the extreme temperatures.

Campus buildings will remain open, and dining halls, libraries and most other campus facilities and services will continue operations. U-M buses and shuttles will operate as scheduled, although delays are possible.

Please remember to dress appropriately when walking in these severe weather conditions. Relatively short periods of exposure to these temperatures at bus stops or walking across campus can be hazardous; all are strongly encouraged to stay indoors.

President Coleman offers a statement following the death of Nelson Mandela yesterday: 

"When the University of Michigan awarded an honorary degree to Nelson Mandela in 1987, it was the first and only time such recognition has been extended in absentia. It was an historic act for an extraordinary individual. At the time, Mr. Mandela was still three years from his release from prison and his future as a Nobel laureate and South Africa's first black president.

"Nelson Mandela was the embodiment of leadership, perseverance and humility. His unwavering commitment to social justice and human equality continually inspires us and will resonate long after his passing."

This week, President Coleman and a delegation of University leaders traveled to India to create new global partnerships.

We have established a partnership with Ashoka University, aiming to provide both universities with opportunities for faculty development & exchange, innovative teaching methods, and student and research scholar exchange. A  similar partnership with National Council of Applied Economic Research, the leading survey research institute in India, was formed.

The University of Michigan Medical School is expanding its collaboration with the All India Institute of Medical Sciences, one of the country's top academic medical programs.

Read more about the delegation's work in India, and details on our new global partnerships here: http://u-mich.me/1asqOhb

To the Campus Community,

As we learn more details about the typhoon devastation in the Philippines, the desire to help grows stronger. 

While no students or faculty were in the Philippines during this terrible storm, our thoughts are with those in the U-M community with Filipino roots or who have family and friends living in the region.

The University of Michigan Health System is working with World Medical Relief to re-purpose medical supplies and equipment for use in areas of greatest need: http://bit.ly/1apUdZu

Numerous relief agencies are working to deliver aid to the region, including the American Red Cross and UNICEF. To help, please consider supporting their work. 

The University has deep ties to the Philippines, dating back nearly 140 years, and includes helping the nation rebuild following World War II. As Filipinos look to the weeks and months ahead, our support will help further that global relationship.

Sincerely,

Mary Sue Coleman

A statement from President Mary Sue Coleman regarding the death of University of Michigan Medical School student Paul DeWolf this week:

"We extend our deepest condolences to Paul's family, friends and colleagues. He was working and training among a close, nurturing community of healers and I know they will help each other through this difficult time. They will need the support of the broader campus community in the weeks and months ahead, and we will provide it."

Throughout 2012, we made an effort towards sustainability on campus through research and action. The results are in, and we effectively reduced our carbon intensity in transportation by 22%, conducted 13 sustainability course projects, and dropped greenhouse gas emissions by 7% per person on campus.

Ruth Bacon Buchanan (also known as Aunt Ruth) corresponded with thousands of Michigan students, faculty, staff and alumni that went off to war in 1941. Throughout the war she wrote a remarkable 17,828 letters; 6,952 birthday cards; 7,398 get-well cards, and mailed 57,000 copies of the Michigan Daily.

Read more of her story, and check out other great stories of our University on the new UMich Heritage site! http://heritage.umich.edu

status_message: As we see these graduates from 1912 accepting their diplomas, we'd like to send congratulations to the University of Michigan 2012 class celebrating commencement today! Go Blue and Beyond!

To the Campus Community,

Our hearts are broken by today's tragic shooting at a Connecticut elementary school.  It is all the more painful because of the number of young children involved, both as victims and witnesses.  Classrooms are places of learning and creativity, and that special environment was shattered for so many today. 

As exams conclude and we turn our attention to home, holidays and family, please join me in holding a place in your heart for those whose lives have been forever changed. 

President Mary Sue Coleman
